Wk16 Mechanism of acute pain medications 

Thursday, July 27, 2017 

5:28 PM 

Nociception 

The detection of noxious stimuli on nociceptors can involve chemical (ASIC, P2X, B1, B2 bradykinin, prostanoid for prostaglandin), mechanical and thermal stimulation. These cause depolarisation in nociceptors, with an action potential conducting the signal. (Nociceptive neurons are high-threshold, associated with substantial cell injury or cell death.) Nociceptive fibers synapse in the dorsal horn onto ascending spinothalamic fibers in the spinothalamic tract. This brings the signal to the brainstem. The brainstem combines this signal with downward modulatory signals from the brain, before the signal is perceived by the correct cortex of the brain. 

 

 

At the synapse 

At the synapse in the spinal cord, 2 key neurotransmitters are used: glutamate and substance P. CGRP is an additional compound employed to ensure the signal is sent. Note slow and fast modulatory responses.  

 

 

Interestingly, nociceptive neurons can release neurotransmitter out of both ends. This allows the nociceptive neuron to facilitate inflammatory process and ensure its own activation until the injury heals.  

 

Describe pharmacologic mechanisms that decrease nociception by altering transmission at the synapse (eg prevention of neurotransmitter release, hyperpolarisation of receiving neuron) 

Nociception can be blocked presynaptically via reduction of calcium influx. Postsynaptically, inhibition is mediated primarily by increased Cl- influx and K+ efflux, causing hyperpolarisation. Receptor targets are m Opioid receptors, GABAB receptors, and alpha-2 adrenergic receptors.  

 

 

Briefly describe the mechanism of opioid drugs on afferent pain pathways 

Opioids (eg morphine, codeine derived from opium) inhibit synaptic transmission. Endogenous opioid peptides include beta-endorphins, enkephalins and dynorphins. There are also synthetic and semi-synthetic opioid drugs.  

 

Endogenous opioids are those released at several CNS sites in response to noxious stimuli and as part of the stress response. However, this doesn’t always occur. Opioids inhibit the synaptic transmission of pain signals, and are agonists that stimulate GPCR opioid receptors m, d, k.  

 

Note that the primary receptor associated with analgesia is m.  

 

 

Note the location of the opioid receptors, both on the nociceptive c-fiber and the afferent fiber at the dorsal horn. This allows both the control of neurotransmitter release and the responsiveness of the ascending fiber.  

 

Pre-synaptic activation of m Opioid receptors 

-Inhibition of adenylyl cyclase to reduce CAMP 

-Inhibition of voltage gated Ca2+ channels 

-Reduced synaptic vesicle mobilisation and hence reduced neurotransmitter release 

 

Post-synaptic activation of m Opioid receptors 

-Activation of G proteins that activate K+ channels 

-K+ efflux hyperpolarises cell to prevent action potential 

 

Note: Opioids impact the brain in altering mood, causing sedation, reducing emotional reaction to pain, and can cause euphoria and consequently dysphoria. At the brainstem, there is an increased activity of neurons providing descending inhibition in the spinal cord to reduce pain.  

 

Briefly describe the adverse effects of opioids on GI function 

-Opioids reduce ACH release, disrupting inter-segment coordination to reduce motility 

-Decreased GIT secretion of enzymes and hormones 

-Resultantly, this causes delayed gastric emptying, enhanced fluid absorption, nausea/vomiting, constipation, abdominal discomfort 

-Absorption of other drugs is modified 

 

 

Briefly describe the adverse effects of opioids on the CNS 

-Decreased activity of the brainstem reduces activity of respiratory center, leads to respiratory depression 

-Activation of the chemoreceptor trigger zone causes severe nausea and vomiting 

-Sedation 

-Tolerance, dependence, addiction
